.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:2: title: "Decision Record: 094 - RCAF-vs-natural-human heuristic"
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:3: description: "ADR for the rubric cli-codex applies per scenario when naturalizing canonical Prompt fields across all manual_testing_playbook packages."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:6:   - "rcaf heuristic adr"
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:7:   - "natural human prompt heuristic"
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:12:     packet_pointer: "skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness"
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:27: # Decision Record: 094 - RCAF-vs-natural-human heuristic
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:35: ## ADR-001: Default canonical playbook Prompt to natural-human voice; reserve RCAF for orchestrator-as-actor scenarios
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:40: The repo has 16 manual_testing_playbook directories with ~498 per-feature scenarios. Every scenario pins a canonical `Prompt:` (or `RCAF Prompt:`) field that's tested for byte-equality against the 9-col scenario table cell. The current convention defaults to RCAF (Role-Context-Action-Format) form: "As a {ROLE}, {ACTION} against {TARGET}. Verify {EXPECTED_OUTCOME}. Return {OUTPUT_FORMAT}."
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:42: The user observed: "The prompts often start with 'As a ....' But that usually won't be added by real humans in normal queries." Real human prompts to an AI are direct: "review my PR", "commit my changes", "fix this bug", "explain what this does". RCAF reads as a templated wrapper around a simple human request.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:44: Inventory of all 16 playbooks shows the existing scenarios already capture both voices: the `Real user request:` field is consistently natural, while the `Prompt:` field is consistently RCAF. The two forms diverge from the same scenario, which is informative — RCAF isn't more accurate, it's more formal.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:47: The canonical `Prompt:` field defaults to natural-human voice. RCAF is reserved for scenarios where the actor IS an AI orchestrator delegating to another tool/AI/agent.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:51: | Use **RCAF** ("As a {ROLE}...") when… | Use **natural-human** when… |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:55: | Internal validation contracts where the orchestrator IS the operator (e.g., "validation operator validates context retrieval against …"). | Most of `Real user request:` field content already in the playbook — that field IS the natural form. |
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:58: **When in doubt: prefer natural-human.** RCAF is the exception, natural is the default.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:60: **Voice guidelines for natural-human prompts**:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:66: **Voice guidelines for RCAF when retained**:
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:74: - Operators running scenarios get prompt phrasing closer to what they'd actually use.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:75: - Cross-AI scenarios (where RCAF is genuinely needed) become more visible because they're the exception, not the default.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:79: - One-time refactor cost: ~280 prompts updated across 16 playbooks (~3 hours wall-clock via cli-codex medium fast).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:85: *Option B: Keep RCAF as the universal default*. Rejected because user feedback is direct and clear; ~56% of scenarios feel formulaic; the existing `Real user request:` field already proves the natural form is preferred when one is forced to pick.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:87: *Option C: Author a third "Natural User Prompt" field alongside RCAF Prompt and Real user request*. Rejected as field bloat; the playbook contract already has too many fields; the right move is to make the canonical Prompt field flexible, not add another.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:89: *Option D: Mechanical regex strip of "As a X, " prefix from all prompts*. Rejected because it discards the genuine RCAF cases (cross-CLI delegation, etc.) and the resulting prose is often grammatically broken.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:91: *Option E: Update sk-doc templates only and leave existing playbooks as-is*. Rejected because the user explicitly asked for "every single playbook in the repo" — the existing prompts are the visible regression coverage and need to be naturalized too.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/094-playbook-prompt-naturalness/decision-record.md:102: ~498 files need targeted prompt-field rewrites. The work is well-bounded (per-scenario classification + dual-location update), templated (heuristic rubric is explicit), and reversible (no code changes, no destructive ops). The orchestrator could do this work directly via Edit tool calls but it would consume orchestrator context for hundreds of small edits.
